  <div class="post">
    <div class="post-title">
	 <a href="http://lyceum.ibiblio.org/2010/05/12/the-lyceum-project-is-shutting-down/" style="text-decoration:none;" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link: The Lyceum project is shutting down">
	 The Lyceum project is shutting down</a>
    </div>


	         <div class="post-body">
	<div>
              	<p>My <a href="http://lyceum.ibiblio.org/2009/03/10/the-future-of-lyceum/">post back in March 2009</a> provoked quite a few comments. Through that channel and some others, I&#8217;ve received a steady trickle of admiration for Lyceum, and pleas to continue its development.</p>
<p>The history of Lyceum has been a curious one. It was my life for something like a year and a half. Interest in it grew steadily as did the rate of feature and bug fix contributions. Then I got a job. After that, I was only able to squeeze in a few maintenance releases. WordPress development steamrolled ahead of me, and soon I wasn&#8217;t able to invest the time to keep it going.</p>
<p>I was hoping that my post last March would stimulate some interest somewhere that could keep the project going. It only would have taken a couple small paid projects to encourage me to invest the couple months to rebootÂ  Lyceum development. That never happened. Also, I&#8217;m pursing other projects now that would not have been compatible with committing to Lyceum.</p>
<p>To this day, it&#8217;s pretty frequent when I mention Lyceum, and people say &#8220;Oh right, I remember that. That project was pretty cool.&#8221; (Maybe they are just trying to be nice). It was a good project, and a good idea, and maybe we&#8217;ll see it come back to life one day.</p>
<p>Maybe sooner than we think. 2010 is a much different place than 2006. It&#8217;s an exciting time for the web, for software development, and for WordPress. WordPress 3.0 is going to merge WordPress and WordPress MU. This bodes extremely well for the code quality, the feature development, the user community, and the contributor community for both WP and WPMU. It also makes it much easier to maintain a branch of the code like Lyceum.</p>
<p>The increasing popularity and power of distributed source control systems is another big help to projects like Lyceum. In 2006 and 2007 I was essentially using undocumented features of Subversion to do crazy merges between disparate repositories. Today, I can use Git or Bazaar or Mercurial to fork directly off of the WordPress subversion repository (or Git if they switch), and cleanly integrate future changes in as structured a workflow as one could hope for.</p>
<p>So if the above things come together, and people start clamoring for a normalized-schema version of MU, and a developer or two emerge who could lead the project, there might be a natural time over the next year or two for Lyceum to start up again. Who knows, maybe it could be a semi-official side project of the WordPress team.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s been great working on Lyceum, and truly great working with the thousands of users, contributors, and fans out there. As of this blog post, consider the Lyceum project officially shut down (however unnecessary that is to say 2+ years after the last code commit).</p>
<p>Until we meet again!</p>
<p>John</p>
<p class="akst_link"><a href="http://lyceum.ibiblio.org/?p=104&amp;akst_action=share-this" onclick="akst_share('104', 'http%3A%2F%2Flyceum.ibiblio.org%2F2010%2F05%2F12%2Fthe-lyceum-project-is-shutting-down%2F', 'The+Lyceum+project+is+shutting+down'); return false;" title="E-mail this, post to del.icio.us, etc." id="akst_link_104" class="akst_share_link" rel="nofollow">Share This (digg, reddit, de.licio.us, email, etc)</a>
</p>    </div>
